WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.440
Hello, everyone. Thank you for coming. My name is Natalia Andrychuk, and I'm a statistical

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:15.580
data scientist at our Center of Excellence. And today I'm here to talk about what it takes

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:23.320
to build a community of engaged R users and how we approach this at Pfizer. But first,

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:28.520
let me take a step back and answer the question of why building community was important for

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:35.439
us. Here's my favorite quote from Alice in Wonderland. My dear, here we must run as fast

00:00:35.439 --> 00:00:41.200
as we can, just to stay in place. And if we want to go anywhere, you must run twice as

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:47.360
fast as that. And in my opinion, this perfectly describes what's happening in the pharma world

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:53.119
when it comes to adoption of R. And I won't be diving into details of why this is happening.

00:00:53.119 --> 00:00:57.639
I just want to let you know that Pfizer is not an exception, and R adoption happening

00:00:57.639 --> 00:01:07.519
fast. So building the community, connecting people and their experiences is very vital

00:01:07.519 --> 00:01:15.199
for success. But what if we approached building the community like the README file for our

00:01:15.199 --> 00:01:21.959
project or package? README file is very essential, and I'm sure a lot of you in this room either

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:27.760
interacted with the README file or created one. This is the first file that programmers

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:33.320
read when they actually approach your project. So let's look at the typical structure of

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:38.279
the README file together, and I'll let you know how this translates into the community

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:45.080
building terms. When you open the README file, the first thing you look for is the installation

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:50.519
instructions, how to install the package. Is it on CRAN? Is it on GitHub? Are there

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:56.959
any dependencies you have to take into account? This is the foundational knowledge you need

00:01:56.959 --> 00:02:02.639
to obtain in order to move forward with installing the package. You can't move forward without

00:02:02.639 --> 00:02:08.440
that. And in the community building terms, this translates into establishing the foundation

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:15.279
for your community. And to be successful in it, you need to assemble a dedicated team

00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:22.440
of colleagues who will take on the community building project and will make it their priority.

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:27.960
And we do have such team at Pfizer, and I'm very lucky to be a part of it. And at Pfizer,

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:37.320
we have the R-SWAT team. This is our SWAT team. It's part of a bigger RCOE team. And

00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:44.639
the SWAT stands for scientific workflows and analytic tools. We're very proud of this acronym.

00:02:44.639 --> 00:02:50.960
We are the internal consultancy group for those parts of organizations that don't have

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:56.600
experts on hand. So we are the art experts. And on top of that, we are the professional

00:02:56.600 --> 00:03:03.039
community builders. Building the community is not our side project. This is one of our

00:03:03.039 --> 00:03:07.839
priorities. So we have the community building initiatives in our semester goals, and we

00:03:07.839 --> 00:03:13.679
treat it as a project deliverables. Because if we won't do that, then there always will

00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:18.320
be the project that's going to supersede community building initiatives, and the process

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:25.039
would be slow. However, it's very important to acknowledge that we won't be able to make

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:30.600
the progress that we made without the help of our IT experts. Because we're our community

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:37.759
builders, and we need our infrastructure to achieve our goals and the goals of our colleagues.

00:03:37.759 --> 00:03:43.320
At Pfizer, we use a suite of professional tools to support our projects, and our IT

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:49.080
experts support all of them. And the SWAT team works closely with IT to define the best

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:55.399
practices. We also have regular check-ins to address any questions or concerns we as

00:03:55.399 --> 00:04:01.759
a team have and our colleagues have. So we're this connector between our programmers and

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:07.679
the IT department. And the relationships we established with the IT colleagues help us

00:04:07.679 --> 00:04:13.559
to support our community. Having tools is great, but we all know that we need a proper

00:04:13.559 --> 00:04:19.640
documentation for those tools. And we needed a single source of truth and a single source

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:25.480
of documentation where our colleagues can access all the documentation regardless of

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:31.959
where they are in the world at any given time. So for us, the R at Pfizer conference became

00:04:31.959 --> 00:04:38.720
this single source of truth. So the conference website is an internal website where we host

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:44.519
all our documentation, how-to articles. We promote best practices. And this is also the

00:04:44.519 --> 00:04:54.559
place where our IT colleagues post all their best practices, guides, and information.

00:04:54.559 --> 00:05:00.799
And the rule of thumb is, if we get the same question from multiple colleagues a few times,

00:05:00.799 --> 00:05:05.920
we need to write a knowledge article on it and post it to the conference website. With

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:11.399
this, we accomplish a few things. So first of all, we're saving ourselves time in the

00:05:11.399 --> 00:05:16.000
long run because we're only publishing the article once. Of course, we need to maintain

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:21.320
it, but the bulk of work done just once. And then the second thing is that everyone will

00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:27.619
get the same uniform advice to the question they ask, the advice that we as a team agreed

00:05:27.619 --> 00:05:31.619
on if this is consolidated in the knowledge article.

00:05:31.619 --> 00:05:38.859
Perfect. We went through the first part of our readme, the foundation part. So let's

00:05:38.859 --> 00:05:44.420
go back to the typical package readme and see what the next section is. And the next

00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:50.619
section is usage. So you install the package, and now it's time to dive in and learn whether

00:05:50.619 --> 00:05:55.739
the key functionality of your package and learn whether the key functions of the package

00:05:55.899 --> 00:06:02.500
are. And in the community building terms, this translates into creating, delivering,

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:07.899
and maintaining proper training for your colleagues. Everyone's learning approach is different,

00:06:07.899 --> 00:06:13.500
and everybody can be in different places when it comes to their R journey. So it was very

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:21.100
important for us to deliver training that will fit everyone.

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:26.299
We all learn programming by doing. Therefore, we create this series of hands-on mini projects

00:06:26.299 --> 00:06:34.420
where our colleagues can get their hands dirty. So far, we have 13 R projects. Those are the

00:06:34.420 --> 00:06:40.380
R Markdown files, and each R Markdown file dedicated to a specific topic can be how to

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:47.779
create a function or visualize the data. And all of the exercises are relevant to clinical

00:06:47.779 --> 00:06:52.980
programming, so they're relevant to our colleagues' day-to-day job. Trainees can access those

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:57.579
exercises at any given time, and they can perform them and complete the challenge at

00:06:57.579 --> 00:07:03.579
the end at their own pace. It's also important to learn from experts.

00:07:03.579 --> 00:07:10.140
Therefore, we make an effort to, once in a while, invite the expert from POSIT or within

00:07:10.140 --> 00:07:14.660
our own Pfizer organization, and they can come in and give a training on a dedicated

00:07:14.660 --> 00:07:20.779
topic. Again, it can be a workflow or a package. And then we record all those sessions. Those

00:07:20.779 --> 00:07:26.700
are typically one- to two-hour sessions, and then we post it to Microsoft Teams channel.

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:32.019
And we have a bunch of recordings, so we divided them into sections. For example, master the

00:07:32.019 --> 00:07:39.380
tidyverse training sessions are the videos where each recording dedicated to, for example,

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:46.459
the tidyverse package. And the R for beginners, those are the videos with the beginner-friendly

00:07:46.459 --> 00:07:53.940
topics. They're very short videos, actually. However, we all know that R is moving fast,

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:57.299
so you recorded the training today, you post it, and then tomorrow they release the new

00:07:57.299 --> 00:08:02.420
version of this package or the new function. So we have a couple of initiatives to keep

00:08:02.420 --> 00:08:07.339
our colleagues updated. In the function of the week initiative, we highlight and we post

00:08:07.339 --> 00:08:11.820
about the function we want to highlight, and we find it very useful into day-to-day

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:17.859
programmer's life. And in the package of the month initiative, every month or every other

00:08:17.859 --> 00:08:23.859
month, we release a little training, the R markdown for the package of the month that

00:08:23.859 --> 00:08:31.179
colleagues can download and go through. We also utilize a form of newsletters to distribute

00:08:31.179 --> 00:08:36.380
knowledge. So there are two types of newsletters we distribute. Advances in our newsletter

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:41.700
is the one that highlights latest and greatest in our community and in our tools, and it's

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:48.340
also pharma-tailored, so it's very Pfizer-focused. And in external outreach newsletter, our colleagues

00:08:48.340 --> 00:08:54.179
who are involved in external initiatives, like FUSE, our consortium, they highlight

00:08:54.179 --> 00:09:02.179
their group's latest updates, upcoming events, and the working group progress. Perfect. We

00:09:02.179 --> 00:09:08.739
finished the second section of our readme, and now let's move on to the last and my favorite

00:09:08.739 --> 00:09:14.859
part on how to contribute back. So in your typical readme package, there's always a section

00:09:14.859 --> 00:09:21.820
on how to contribute back, because open source projects, they encourage collaboration and

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:26.940
they encourage innovation. And maybe you downloaded the package, you played with it a bit, and

00:09:26.940 --> 00:09:33.500
then you found a bug and you want to propose the solution, or maybe you would want to request

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:38.659
the feature. And in the community-building terms, this is actually perfect as is. That

00:09:38.659 --> 00:09:46.419
doesn't translate. And I want to emphasize that I notice this is a common misconception,

00:09:46.419 --> 00:09:52.659
that you have to be a seasoned programmer in order to contribute back to the community.

00:09:53.419 --> 00:09:59.140
To prove that this is not true, I want to show you a quick example. This is the issues

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:06.219
tab of the GitHub page for the very well-known package, usethis. And you can see there are

00:10:06.219 --> 00:10:11.419
a lot of issues filed for this package. This package is by thousands of programmers. And

00:10:11.419 --> 00:10:19.140
each issue has a tag associated. And amongst those tags, you can find a good first issue.

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:24.739
This shows that even the most complex projects, that they have tasks that can be achieved

00:10:24.739 --> 00:10:32.099
and that can be done by beginner programmers. So by picking up this issue, working on it,

00:10:32.099 --> 00:10:36.500
and contributing the results of your work back, you're helping yourself, you're learning

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:41.099
new things, as well as helping programmers who are developing the package and programmers

00:10:41.099 --> 00:10:46.859
who are going to use this package. We kept this in mind as community builders when we

00:10:46.859 --> 00:10:51.739
were creating the initiatives and tools where our colleagues can contribute back. So let's

00:10:51.739 --> 00:10:57.700
take a look at a few of those. First and foremost, anyone can join the R and

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:03.780
Fizer Microsoft Teams channel, comprising over 1,100 colleagues so far. It's a great

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:09.419
resource for sharing news and answering and asking questions. And sometimes when you're

00:11:09.419 --> 00:11:14.619
battling the programming issue, it might seem like you're the only one in this world facing

00:11:14.619 --> 00:11:19.859
this very niche issue. But a lot of times you're not. There's always someone out there

00:11:19.859 --> 00:11:25.179
who already solved this issue and has a solution for you. Or there's someone who's battling

00:11:25.179 --> 00:11:31.299
the same issue and you can join forces and look for the solution together. So by asking

00:11:31.299 --> 00:11:36.219
the question on Microsoft Teams channel, our colleagues are getting closer to solving the

00:11:36.219 --> 00:11:41.580
issues they have. And then once they build the expertise, they can also contribute to

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:49.700
the community, give back, and assist others by answering their questions.

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:53.940
Another great initiative I would like to highlight, one of my favorites, is the Book Club. We

00:11:53.940 --> 00:11:59.479
established the Book Club earlier this year and we picked an R for Data Science second

00:11:59.479 --> 00:12:04.739
edition book. And this is a great initiative for our colleagues to collaborate and put

00:12:04.739 --> 00:12:11.179
the time dedicated to learning new things in their day-to-day schedule. So we initially

00:12:11.179 --> 00:12:18.099
had 130 people sign up for the Book Club. And our colleagues were divided into 14 different

00:12:18.099 --> 00:12:23.099
groups. And the geography for those groups spans from North America through Europe to

00:12:23.099 --> 00:12:29.619
Asia. And we divided those groups so that it's the same time zone and also we have different

00:12:29.619 --> 00:12:34.500
expertise level in the same group for our colleagues. And each group has a dedicated

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:39.739
group lead. And throughout the time of like working on this initiative and leading one

00:12:39.739 --> 00:12:45.020
of the groups, we learned that one of the biggest obstacle for this particular initiative

00:12:45.020 --> 00:12:50.700
is the day job commitments. As the day job commitments increase, it becomes harder for

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:57.059
colleagues to join the session and read the book on a dedicated scheduled basis. However,

00:12:57.059 --> 00:13:01.659
for those teams that became tight-knit and for those colleagues who are very consistent

00:13:01.659 --> 00:13:07.419
in reading the book and joining the session, even if they haven't had a chance to read

00:13:07.419 --> 00:13:13.020
the chapter that week, we received incredibly positive feedback and willingness to join

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:19.580
Book Clubs in the future. The Community of Practice event is a monthly

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:25.299
meeting where we have two 20-minute presentations followed by 10-minute questions. And this

00:13:25.299 --> 00:13:31.539
is not an exclusive event. Anyone can get on the schedule and showcase their art projects,

00:13:31.539 --> 00:13:38.059
lessons learned, and ask for the feedback. The presentations vary in scope to keep all

00:13:38.059 --> 00:13:44.739
colleagues engaged. And this is a formal event. So the presentations are recorded and they're

00:13:44.739 --> 00:13:52.500
prepared in advance. So this is one of the ways you can contribute back. However, there

00:13:52.500 --> 00:14:01.020
is another one which is informal event. We adopted the Data Science Hangout event led

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:07.020
by Rachel Dempsey at Posit. So if you haven't heard of the Data Science Hangout, it happens

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:12.419
every Thursday at noon Eastern Standard Time. And anyone from the data science community

00:14:12.419 --> 00:14:18.900
can join. So please join if you haven't already. So similarly, our internal Art Advisor Hangout

00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:23.500
happens every other Wednesday. And anyone from Pfizer interested in our programming

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:30.380
can join. During this event, we invite a featured colleague. It's our guest. And we ask our

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:35.539
colleague different questions. For example, their art journey, what excites them about

00:14:35.539 --> 00:14:42.299
art, what projects they're working on. And this is the informal event. So all the questions

00:14:42.299 --> 00:14:50.099
are audience-led. And this is also not recorded, just in case you want to ask interesting questions.

00:14:50.099 --> 00:14:55.419
And here you have it. We successfully went through all of the sections of our readme.

00:14:55.419 --> 00:15:00.020
And now it's time to summarize why we put so much effort into creating this community

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:11.619
and building it. Building a community is like putting the puzzle pieces together. It's hard

00:15:11.619 --> 00:15:18.820
at times. It's time-consuming, but very rewarding. Because engaged community solves business

00:15:18.820 --> 00:15:24.619
problems faster in a more efficient way by connecting people and their experiences. It

00:15:24.619 --> 00:15:32.500
promotes knowledge sharing, collaboration, innovation. And if you are just starting your

00:15:32.500 --> 00:15:38.419
community building journey or thinking about one, just remember to be patient. We at Pfizer

00:15:38.419 --> 00:15:44.380
are trying out different formats to keep our community engaged. And some of them are getting

00:15:44.380 --> 00:15:50.659
traction right away. Others take time to get on track. However, we know that being consistent

00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:56.099
and persistent and listening to our colleagues' feedback is the key to figuring out what works

00:15:56.099 --> 00:16:01.820
best for the organization. And with that, I would like to thank you. Please feel free

00:16:01.820 --> 00:16:06.820
to scan the QR code to connect and view some other resources that I linked.

